('generate_with_fc', '{"args":[],"func":"generate_with_fc","kwargs":{"functions":[],"messages":[{"content":"Based on the persona profile, generate a brief description of the character\'s home (bedroom/room) and representative objects.\\n\\nProfile:\\nName: Aaron Whitfield\\nAppearance: Standing 6\'1\\" and roughly 180 lbs, Aaron has a fair (~20%) look defined by angular cheekbones, deep-set slate-blue eyes, and a pointed chin perpetually shadowed by two-day stubble. His dirty-blond hai ... (763 more chars omitted)\\nDescription: Aaron is a freelance journalist and aspiring novelist who moved to Bremer Apartment in 2019. He\'s working on a debut novel about immigrant families in New York while scraping together income from magazine features and copywriting gigs. He carries guilt over his estranged relationship with his father and channels his emotional complexity into his writing.\\nDetails: Aaron moved into a small one-bedroom on the fourth floor in January 2019. He met Leo first — they share a wall, and Aaron knocked one evening to apologize for typing too loudly at 2 AM. They bonded over being quiet, cerebral men living in a city that rewards loudness. Aaron frequents the corner coffee shop where Jamal works, often spending four or five hours writing at the window table. He met Katie through Leo in spring 2019 and they developed an easy, teasing friendship; she sometimes reads passages from his novel drafts aloud in funny accents to loosen him up. He met Mike on the rooftop in summer 2019 and they occasionally drink together after Mike\'s bar shifts. Aaron\'s father was diagnosed with early-onset dementia in late 2019. Aaron hasn\'t visited and tells no one except Leo, who overheard him on the phone. His novel is about three generations of a Dominican family in Washington Heights, drawn from interviews he conducted for the Atlantic piece. He worries constantly about whether a white man from Ohio has the right to tell that story. His freelance income is inconsistent — some months flush, some months he eats ramen for a week. He\'s never married, had one serious relationship in Chicago that ended when she said he loved his work more than her.\\n\\nOutput JSON: {\\"description\\": <2-4 sentences>, \\"objects\\": [4-6 item names]}\\nOutput in en.","role":"user"}],"model":"my-vllm-model","tool_choice":"none"}}')
